		<h2><a name="install" class="Q">Install the program</a></h2>
		<p>First, download the program by one of the methods found on the <a href="downloads.html">downloads</a> page.
		Open a terminal and change the working directory to the location of the file download.</p>
		<p>If the program was downloaded through sourceforge, it must be uncompressed using the following command (replacing it with current version number):</p>
		<p class="codebox">tar -xvf vcfools.0.X.XX.tar.gz</p>
		<p>Now change to the vcftools directory and compile the program. If the program was instead downloaded through subversion, change to the specified target directory.</p>
		<p class="codebox">cd vcfools/
		<br>make</p>
		<p>This will compile both the PERL API and the C++ executable. By default, the compiled programs will now be in the <b>vcftools/bin/</b> directory.
		Some common compiler errors may appear, such as not being able to locate <b>Vcf.pm</b> or not being able to locate <b>zlib</b>.
		Please make sure zlib is installed and that the <b>PERL5LIB</b> path is set correctly.</p>
		
		<h2><a name="run" class="Q">Run the program</a></h2>
		<p>The executable can be <b>run</b> without any input just to test if it is working.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools</p>
		<p>It will return information about the program such as the version number and authors. If it returns this information, then the program has been compiled correctly.</p>
		    
		<h2><a name="file" class="Q">Get basic file statistics</a></h2>
		<p>The executable can be run with only an input VCF or BCF file without any other options to determine the contents of the file.
		To specify an input file you must use the one of the input options ( <b>--vcf</b>, <b>--gzvcf</b>, or <b>--bcf </b> ) depending on the type of file.
		For example, for a VCF file called <b>input_data.vcf</b> the following command could be run.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf</p>
		<p>It will return information about the file such as the <b>number of variants</b> and the <b>number of individuals</b> in the file.</p>
		<p>Beginning with vcftools v0.1.12, the program can also take input in from <b>stdin</b> instead of specifying a file name. To do this, use any of the normal file type input options followed by the dash <b>-</b> character.</p>
		<p class="codebox">zcat input_data.vcf.gz | ./bin/vcftools --vcf -</p>

		<h2><a name="filter" class="Q">Applying a filter</a></h2>
		<p>Some of the power of vcftools involves the ability to filter out variants or individuals based on the values within the file.
		There are many such filtering options to specify. To filter the sites within a file based upon their location in genome, use the options
		<b>--chr</b>, <b>--from-bp</b>, and <b>--to-bp</b> to specify the region.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --chr 1 --from-bp 1000000 --to-bp 2000000</p>
		<p>After running this line, the program will return the amount of sites in the file that are included in the chromosomal region chr1:1000000-2000000.
		This option can be modified to work with any desired region.</p>

		<h2><a name="newvcf" class="Q">Writing to a new VCF file</a></h2>
		<p>VCFtools can do many different analyses on the variants that pass through the filters or simply <b>write those variants out to a new file</b>.
		This function is helpful for creating subsets of VCF files or just removing unwanted variants from VCF files. To write out the variants that pass through filters use the <b>--recode</b> option.
		In addition, use <b>--recode-INFO-all</b> to include all data from the INFO fields in the output. By default INFO fields are not written because many filters will alter the variants in a file which renders
		the INFO values incorrect.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --chr 1 --from-bp 1000000 --to-bp 2000000 --recode --recode-INFO-all</p>
		<p>In this example, vcftools will create a new VCF file containing only variants within that chromosomal region while keeping all INFO fields included in the orignal file.</p>
		<p>Any files written out by vcftools will be in the current working directory and have the prefix <i>./out.SUFFIX</i> by default.
		To change the path, specify the new path using the option <b>--out</b> followed by the desired path. The program will add a suffix to that path based on the chosen output function.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --chr 1 --from-bp 1000000 --to-bp 2000000 --recode --out /home/usr/data/subset</p>

		<h2><a name="streamvcf" class="Q">Writing out to screen</a></h2>
		<p>Beginning with vcftools v0.1.12, the program can also write out to screen instead of having the program write to a specified path. Using the options
		<b>--stdout</b> or <b>-c</b> will redirect all output to standard out. The screen can then be piped into other programs or written out to a specified file name.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --chr 1 --from-bp 1000000 --to-bp 2000000 --recode --stdout | more</p>
		<p>The above example will output the resulting file to screen one line at a time for <b>quick inspection</b> of the results.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --chr 1 --from-bp 1000000 --to-bp 2000000 --recode -c > /home/usr/data/subset.vcf</p>
		<p>The above example will redirect the output and <b>write</b> it to the specified file name.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --chr 1 --from-bp 1000000 --to-bp 2000000 --recode -c | gzip -c > /home/usr/data/subset.vcf.gz</p>
		<p>The above example will redirect the output into <b>gzip</b> (assuming it is installed) for <b>compression</b>, and then gzip will write the file to the specified destination.</p>

		<h2><a name="convertbcf" class="Q">Converting a VCF file to BCF</a></h2>
		<p>Beginning with vcftools v0.1.11, the program has the ability to read and write <b>BCF files</b>. This means that the program can also convert files between the two formats.
		This is accomplished in a similar way as the above example, instead using the <b>--recode-bcf</b> option. All output BCF files are automatically compressed using BGZF.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --recode-bcf --recode-INFO-all --out /home/usr/data/converted_output</p>
		
		<h2><a name="comparevcf" class="Q">Comparing two files</a></h2>
		<p>Using vcftools, two VCF files (or BCF files) can be compared to determine which sites and individuals are shared between them. The first file is declared using the input file options just like any other output function. The second file must be
		specified using <b>--diff</b>, <b>--gzdiff</b>, or <b>--diff-bcf</b>. There are also advanced options to determine additional discordance between the two files.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --diff other_data.vcf --out /home/usr/data/compare</p>
		
		<h2><a name="freq" class="Q">Getting allele frequency</a></h2>
		<p>There are many <b>output functions</b> in vcftools, one of the most common being the allele frequency function. It allows users to determine the frequency of each allele over all individuals in a VCF file.
		To accomplish this, the <b>--freq</b> argument is used. Many of the other output functions can be used similarly to this, yet some output functions require additional arguments.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --bcf input_data.bcf --freq --out /home/usr/data/output</p>
		<p>The above is an example of getting frequency information from a BCF file. All output functions have default suffixes for the output file. The output file will be written to <i>/home/usr/data/output.frq</i> in this case.</p>
		
		<h2><a name="depth" class="Q">Getting sequencing depth information</a></h2>
		<p>Other useful output functions in vcftools include functions for <b>summarizing sequencing depth</b> for each individual or for each site. Just like the allele frequency example above, this output function follows the same basic model.
		</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --depth -c > /home/usr/data/depth_summary.txt</p>
		<p>The program also has the ability to summarize the depth over all individuals at one site. In the following example, that information is only desired for sites that have no missing data.
		The user includes the <b>--max-missing</b> argument to remove all sites with any missing data. The vcftools command line can accept a combination of many filters with the desired output function.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --site-depth --max-missing 1 --out /home/usr/data/site_depth_summary</p>		
		
		<h2><a name="ld" class="Q">Getting linkage disequilibrium statistics</a></h2>
		<p>Linkage disequilibrium between sites can be determined as well. This is accomplished using the <b>--hap-r2</b>, <b>--geno-r2</b>, or <b>--geno-chisq</b> arguments.
		Since the program must do pairwise site comparisons, this analysis can take a while, so it is recommended to filter the sites first or use one of the other options (<b>--ld-window</b>, <b>--ld-window-bp</b> or <b>--min-r2</b>) to reduce the number of comparisons.
		In this example, the program will only compare sites within 50,000 base pairs of one another.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --hap-r2 --ld-window-bp 50000 --out ld_window_50000</p>
		
		<h2><a name="fst" class="Q">Getting Fst population statistics</a></h2>
		<p>The vcftools program can also calculate <b>Fst statistics</b> between individuals of different populations. It is an estimate calculated in accordance to Weir and Cockerham’s 1984 paper. This is one output function that requires extra arguments.
		The user must supply text files that contain <b>lists of individuals</b> (one per line) that are members of each population. The function will work with multiple populations if multiple <b>--weir-fst-pop</b> arguments are used.
		The following example shows how to calculate a per-site Fst calculation with two populations. There are more arguments that can be used in conjunction with this function, such as <b>--fst-window-size</b> and <b>--fst-window-step</b>.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --weir-fst-pop population_1.txt --weir-fst-pop population_2.txt --out pop1_vs_pop2</p>
		
		<h2><a name="plink" class="Q">Converting VCF files to PLINK format</a></h2>
		<p>The vcftools program can convert VCF files into formats convenient for use in other programs. One such example is the ability to convert into PLINK format.
		The following function will output the variants in <b>.ped</b> and <b>.map</b> files.</p>
		<p class="codebox">./bin/vcftools --vcf input_data.vcf --plink --chr 1 --out output_in_plink</p>
		
